title: Fernhill phrasebooks — the night changes the voice (ADR-250 E2E)
story: fernhill
description: The unreliable-narrator spine (ADR-250 D9). vane-mood lives
  only in the two books — evening-voice (the default book) speaks until
  the turn-14 midnight flip, then midnight-voice wins arbitration.
  vane-story is story text no book may beat, in both states. vane-quiet
  is covered only by the default book and still renders at midnight
  (per-key fallthrough). Each book keeps its OWN first-time counter for
  vane-mood: if counters were keyed by the bare key, midnight's first
  examine would show a second-variant text — the assertions below
  distinguish per-(book, key) from shared state.

---

# Evening: the default book speaks; its first-time counter advances.
> examine the weathervane
[OK: contains "noses the evening breeze"]

> examine the weathervane
[OK: contains "sits easy in the last of the light"]

# Story text beats every book, in every state.
> push the weathervane
[OK: contains "same one story it always tells"]

> touch the weathervane
[OK: contains "keeps its own counsel"]

# Cross the turn-14 midnight transition (the long night sequence).
[DO]
> wait
[OK: contains_any "Time passes" "last light"]
[UNTIL "the last light goes out of the sky"]

# Midnight: midnight-voice wins arbitration — and starts at ITS OWN
# first variant (per-(book, key) counters, ADR-250 D5).
> examine the weathervane
[OK: contains "swings hard north"]

> examine the weathervane
[OK: contains "holds north"]

# The story override is stable across the flip.
> push the weathervane
[OK: contains "same one story it always tells"]

# midnight-voice does not cover vane-quiet — the default book still
# supplies it (fallthrough is per key, never per book).
> touch the weathervane
[OK: contains "keeps its own counsel"]
